In 2018 this emoji was the focus of a grassroots campaign on Twitter (now X) where users of the platform began using this emoji more frequently. This was to update the least-used emoji on emojitracker.com (as tracked by the @leastUsedEmoji Twitter bot) from the Aerial Tramway to another emoji. In May 2025 this emoji was also used within YouTube comments to signify laughter or approval or to create confusion for people not in the know. name: Alembic
description: An apparatus for distilling, as used in medieval alchemy . Generally depicted as a round flask with a neck angled down to the right. Positioned on a short stand and containing a mysterious green, purple, or blue liquid. Commonly used for various content concerning chemistry and science more generally. May represent various liquids, such as potions or medicines, as well as metaphorical laboratories and experiments. Thanks to the alembicâ€™s association with alchemy, this emoji may also convey a sense of magic. And, thanks to its resemblance to a glass pipe, some use the emoji to represent a bong or other drug paraphernalia. Samsungâ€™s design previously featured a copper still, as used for making whiskey .
Alembic was approved as part of Unicode 4.1 in 2005 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

Available as an Apple Animoji . Apple previously displayed a similar looking alien head in a box as a placeholder for an unknown emoji, but now shows a boxed question mark.

Most major platforms style their design after aliens in classic arcade games like Space Invaders , rendering it purple and pixellated, as if in 8-bit graphics. May be used of topics concerning extraterrestrial life, outer space, gaming, and computing, but also enjoys a range of idiosyncratic applications, such as conveying a sense of weirdness, wackiness, or excitement, given that the emoji looks like it is raising its arms shouting Yay! on many platforms. May also be used to reference the streaming platform Twitch , given that the emojiâ€™s color resembles the Twitch logo and both are strongly linked to gaming culture. Samsungâ€™s design previously resembled an octopus , with an even earlier Samsung design featuring a big-brained alien , Ã  la Star Trek . Earlier designs from Google and Microsoft depicted more cartoon-like alien monsters.
Alien Monster was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

May also be used in relation to the zodiac sign of Aquarius , the Water-Bearer. Not to be confused with âš±ï¸ Funeral Urn .

description: A yellow face with a frowning mouth and eyes and eyebrows scrunched downward in anger. Conveys varying degrees of anger, from grumpiness and irritation to disgust and outrage. May also represent someone acting tough or being mean. Samsungâ€™s design previously featured a reddish face with clenched teeth and wrinkled chin. Googleâ€™s design also previously featured a reddish face, while Facebookâ€™s and Microsoft's earlier designs had clenched teeth.
Angry Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

Its Unicode name, Imp , alludes to a small demon in folklore, though the smiley is commonly used to represent devils and devilish behavior, especially around Halloween . It is also used to convey various sentiments of anger or ideas of evil. More menacing than its counterpart, ğŸ˜ˆ Smiling Face With Horns . name: Cow
description: A cow, a bovine farmed for its meat or milk. Depicted in full profile on all fours facing left with a black-and-white patched coat (as a Holstein Friesian ) and, on many platforms, a pink udder and horns. May be used to represent the animal, its food products, or black-and-white coloring. See also ğŸ® Cow Face . Microsoft's cow was previously brown, as was Facebook's , which had a bell around its neck.
Cow was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Cow Face
description: A friendly, cartoon-styled face of a cow looking straight ahead. Variously depicted as a white, brown, or multicolored cow face with a neutral expression, short horns, and a pink or brown muzzle. Often used with a more affectionate tone than the full-bodied ğŸ„ Cow . Available as an Apple Animoji . Facebookâ€™s design once featured a more lifelike, brown cow face.
Cow Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Cowboy Hat Face
description: Yee-haw! A yellow smiley wearing a wide-brimmed, brown-leather cowboy hat. Its smile varies across platforms. May convey a sense of exuberance, whimsy, confidence, adventure, or other sentiments. Several vendors, including Apple, feature the same expression as their ğŸ˜ƒ Grinning Face With Big Eyes .
Cowboy Hat Face was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 under the name "Face with Cowboy Hat" and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

name: Crab
description: A crab, a squat crustacean with pincers. Depicted as a reddish-orange crab (as cooked) shown from above, with a round, shelled body, shorted, tentacle-like eyes, and ten legs, the top two of which are large pincers. May be used to represent crab as food or metaphorical senses of crab (e.g., crabby ). Often used to represent â™‹ Cancer , the Crab, in the Western zodiac. Not to be confused with ğŸ¦ Lobster . Facebookâ€™s pincers have black tips, as do Huawei's.
Crab was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Crayon
description: A crayon, as children use to color. Depicted as red on most platforms with two black stripes on its label, resembling a Crayola crayon . Positioned at a 45Â° angle, its tip at the lower left. Commonly used for various content concerning drawing, colors, arts and crafts, and schooling. WhatsAppâ€™s crayon is green while Facebookâ€™s is orange.

description: The backside of a credit card, showing the magnetic strip and signature. Color and detail vary across platforms, but often shown as gold, silver, or blue. May be used for banking and other ID cards as well for various content concerning money, including payment. Some vendors feature easter eggs: Appleâ€™s design features John Appleseed in the signature and a security code of 448 and Facebookâ€™s design features founder Mark Zuckerbergâ€™s signature and a security code of 123. Samsungâ€™s design previously included the initials KJH .

name: Crescent Moon
description: A crescent moon, as in its waxing crescent phase. Depicts the moon as a thin, golden crescent, curving to the right and not displaying the remaining outline of the moon. May be used for the moon more generally and saying good night. May be used in association with â˜ªï¸ Star and Crescent , a popular but unofficial symbol of Islam. As of March 2019, sending this emoji over Facebook Messenger activates dark mode . See also ğŸŒ’ Waxing Crescent Moon . Googleâ€™s moon once resembled a waning crescent moon, Twitter and Facebook's moons were previously silver.

name: Cricket
description: A cricket, a hopping insect that makes a chirping sound. Depicted as a brown or green cricket in full profile on its six legs facing left, with long antennae and large, bent back legs. May resemble or be used to represent a grasshopper (including locusts) and other bugs . May also be used to represent metaphorical crickets , or "silence," as of a disapproving or uninterested audience. Not to be confused with ğŸ Cricket Game , the sport. Google's cricket was previously green.
Cricket was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017 and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

name: Cricket Game
description: A cricket bat, with a cricket ball also shown. May be displayed with a wicket present.
Cricket Game was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015 under the name "Cricket Bat and Ball" and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Crocodile
description: A crocodile, a stealthy reptile with massive jaws. Generally depicted as a light-green crocodile on all fours, with its long tail curving down to its toothed jaws, facing left. May resemble and be used for an alligator. Facebook's crocodile is opening its jaws. Samsungâ€™s design previously resembled a kind of cartoon dinosaur.
Crocodile was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Cross Mark
description: A large red cross mark, displayed in the shape of a letter X and similar to a multiplication sign .

name: Crossed Fingers

Crossed Fingers was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 under the name "Hand with Index and Middle Fingers Crossed" and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

Crossed Flags was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

description: A gold crown with jewels on the sides. Representative of a King , Queen , or other form of Royalty. May be used to discuss power, wealth, or success more broadly. Used in the 'You dropped this ğŸ‘‘' meme format, where the crown is figuratively returned to someone being praised for greatness, confidence, leadership, or a powerful statement.
Crown was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Crutch
description: A basic crutch made of metal and rubber.
Crutch was approved as part of Unicode 14.0 in 2021 and added to Emoji 14.0 in 2021.

name: Crying Cat
description: A cartoon cat variant of ğŸ˜¢ Crying Face . Depicted as yellow on major platforms.
Crying Cat was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name "Crying Cat Face" and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Crying Face
description: A yellow face with raised eyebrows and a slight frown, shedding a single, blue tear from one eye down its cheek. May convey a moderate degree of sadness or pain, usually less intensely than ğŸ˜­ Loudly Crying Face . Not to be confused with ğŸ˜¥ Sad but Relieved Face , ğŸ˜ª Sleepy Face , or other emojis with tear or sweat droplets. Samsungâ€™s design previously featured tears welling up in both eyes. This emoji has a cat variant, ğŸ˜¿ Crying Face .
Crying Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Crystal Ball
description: A crystal ball , as a fortune teller or clairvoyant gazes into to tell the future. Depicted as a sparkling , purple or blue crystal orb resting on a stand. Commonly used for various content concerning magic, alternative spirituality, and (predicting) the future. May also be used for its shape or color more generally.
Crystal Ball was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Cucumber
description: A long, green cucumber with bumpy skin. Resembles its derived product, a pickle or gherkin, on many platforms, except on Apple and WhatsApp, which depict it with light-green, seed-y slices.
Cucumber was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

name: Cup with Straw
description: A drinking cup with a straw. Depicted on many platforms as a disposable cup with a lid and bendy straw, as used to serve soft drinks at fast-food restaurants. May be used for a range of non-alcoholic beverages, including milkshakes, smoothies, juice, and to-go beverages. Color and design vary by platform. Twitter's design suggests a glass of water , while Samsung's previously displayed a Slightly Smiling Face on a red label.
Cup with Straw was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017 and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

name: Cupcake
description: An individual cupcake in a liner topped with a swirl of frosting and sprinkles. The style of cupcake widely varies across platforms. The cake may be sponge or chocolate, the frosting pink or white, and the sprinkles rainbow or red. Can be used as a playful reference to a person's "buttocks," inspired by the slang term "cake."
Cupcake was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018 and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

name: Curling Stone
description: A curling stone used in the sport of curling. Generally depicted with a red handle, though WhatsApp's design features a blue handle.
Curling Stone was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017 and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

name: Curly Hair
description: An emoji component displaying a person's curly hair. Intended for use within emoji sequences.
Curly Hair was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018 under the name "Emoji Component Curly Hair" and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.
alert: ğŸ¦³While given emoji presentation on select platforms, this emoji component was intended to be used exclusively within emoji sequences. This means this emoji is excluded from most emoji keyboards.

name: Curly Loop
description: A curled loop, which is shown in black on most platforms. Previously displayed as a blue ribbon on Samsung devices. Similar to the Double Curly Loop but with only a single loop.
Curly Loop was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Currency Exchange
description: A symbol for exchanging of two currencies. Most commonly displayed as a dollar symbol , with arrows to and from a yen symbol . Google and Samsung's designs previously showed banknotes and coins in yen , dollars , euros and pounds .
Currency Exchange was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Curry Rice
description: A plate of orange-brown curry with vegetables or meat , served with a mound of white rice . May represent kare-raisu , or Japanese curry , though commonly associated with India and other Asian cuisines.
Curry Rice was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name "Curry and Rice" and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Custard
description: A golden-yellow custard dessert, as a crÃ¨me caramel or flan , topped with a layer of caramel. Shown on a plate, molded in a ramekin-shape and often in a pool of caramel sauce.
Custard was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Customs
description: A customs officer inspecting luggage . May be shown on signage at airports or other border crossings. Not to be confused with the passport control emoji .
Customs was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Cut of Meat
description: A cut of uncooked red meat, as a T-bone or rib-eye steak, with the light, white marbling of fat. May be used for sexual slang .
Cut of Meat was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017 and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

name: Cyclone
description: An icon used to represent a cyclone . Some versions of this emoji show a spiral shape, which may be used for decorative purposes. In May 2025 it was reported that the Claude Opus 4 AI model had an unexpected fixation on this emoji. This emoji is not supported in Twitter / X names, possibly in an attempt to minimize confusion with a verified checkmark. Learn more here .
Cyclone was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Dagger
description: A pointed knife with a steel blade, as used for thrusting in close combat. Generally depicted as double-edged with a black, brown or gold cross-shaped hilt and positioned at 45Â° angle, often with its tip at the lower left. description: A glowing, five-point gold star. Depicted as â­ Star with stylized bursts in between its points, representing glowing or twinkling. name: Goat
description: A goat, a sturdy, hoofed animal raised for its meat and milk. Depicted as a light brown, white, or multicored goat in full profile on all fours facing left, a scraggly beard, upright tail, and brown or yellow horns curving back. Frequently used as a visual shorthand for the slang expression GOAT , or the Great of All Time , often said of athletes and in particular the late Kobe Bryant . Often considered one of the 12 animals of the Chinese zodiac . Also often used to represent â™‘ Capricorn in the Western zodiac. Apple , Google , and Samsungâ€™s goats were previously white, as a Saanen goat . Facebookâ€™s design previously featured only a goat face.
Goat was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Goblin
description: A menacing, red mask featuring a grotesquely long nose, angry eyes, and bushy eyebrows and mustache. Depicts a tengu , a proud trickster figure in Japanese folklore. May popularly denote evil, anger, cruel or mischievous behavior, and sexual suggestion, due to the phallic appearance of its nose. May also represent supernatural or figurative trolls, goblins, and other such beings. This emoji predates the inclusion of emojis within Unicode . It was first added to early Japanese emoji keyboards in 2003 by au by KDDI .
Goblin was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name "Japanese Goblin" and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Goggles

name: Goose
description: A white goose in full profile. Can be used to talk about the actual animal. Can also be used in the context of idioms including silly goose , wild goose chase , or what's good for the goose is good for the gander . Can also be used to talk about goosebumps or goose pimples . Might be used in reference to the children's game duck duck goose .

name: Gorilla

Twitterâ€™s designs previously featured a black and gray gorilla face with a neutral expression and prominent forehead and jaw. Google , Samsung , and Facebookâ€™s designs also previously featured only a gorilla face. This emoji is considered racist in some contexts , particularly when used to disparage, insult, and abuse people with dark skin, especially Black people.
Gorilla was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

name: Graduation Cap

name: Grapes

Grapes was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Green Circle
description: A circle shown in the color of green. As with other color-based shape emojis (most notably the hearts ), this emoji may be used to express an affinity with or appreciation for various people, places, groups, objects, or ideas associated with the same color. In February 2025, this emoji became associated with the Green Party in Canada. The party changed its logo to a similar-looking green circle icon and referenced the emoji during its announcement.
Green Circle was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 under the name "Large Green Circle" and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Green Heart
description: A green heart emoji, often used alongside other colored hearts . As with the other color-based hearts, this emoji is often also used to express an affinity with or appreciation for various people, places, groups, objects, or ideas associated with the same color. For example, this emoji is frequently used on Twitter/X in reference to the Korean boy band NCT . Shown with beads of sweat on an orange and pink heart in previous versions of Android .

Green Salad was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

name: Green Square
description: A square shown in the color of green. As with other color-based shape emojis (most notably the hearts ), this emoji may be used to express an affinity with or appreciation for various people, places, groups, objects, or ideas associated with the same color. When players of the word game Wordle share their results on social platforms the results are represented through a series of green, yellow , and black or white square emojis. This emoji indicates that the player guessed a correct letter in its right place. Additionally, in May 2021, this emoji was occasionally shown in X/Twitter names in support of Taproot , a Bitcoin fork (potential feature change) that would allow additional privacy measures for transactions.
Green Square was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 under the name "Large Green Square" and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Harp
description: A harp â€“ a triangular stringed musical instrument that is played by having its vertical strings plucked with the fingers. Closely linked to traditional music in many cultures, the harp holds a particularly strong connection to Ireland, where it serves as the official emblem of the Irish government and the iconic logo of the well-known Irish brewer, Guinness.
Harp was approved as part of Unicode 16.0 in 2024 and added to Emoji 16.0 in 2024.

name: Hatching Chick
description: A baby chicken (chick), hatching from an egg and seeing the world for the first time. Depicted as a yellow chick with an orange beak facing forward in the cracked, bottom half of a white egg, generally shown flapping its wings with a cute facial expression. Often used with an affectionate tone. May be used to represent various types of baby birds. May also be used to represent chicken foods (e.g., poultry , eggs ), spring , Easter , or slang senses of chick . Not to be confused with ğŸ¤ Baby Chick or ğŸ¥Front-Facing Baby Chick (out of its egg), though their applications overlap. See also ğŸ” Chicken and ğŸ“ Rooster . Twitter and Facebook's designs do not include wings. Google's design previously featured motion lines around the chick's wings, indicating flapping. Facebook's design previously showed part of the egg atop the chick's head.
Hatching Chick was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Helicopter
description: A helicopter, which can hover in the air. Often seen in emergency circumstances such as transporting patients to a hospital , or for police or fire-fighting activity.
Helicopter was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Herb
description: An herb, a plant used in cooking or medicine. Depicted as a green sprig, as of basil, sage, or oregano, generally with five or seven leaves. May be used for various content concerning cooking, herbal medicine, and plant life more generally. Occasionally used as slang for marijuana. Not to be confused with ğŸŒ± Seedling , though their applications may overlap.
Herb was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Hibiscus
description: A pink hibiscus , a flower that grows in warm climates. Depicted as a single, deep-pink hibiscus flower with green leaves and prominent, yellow stamen. Commonly used for Valentineâ€™s Day , Motherâ€™s Day , and other special occasions. May be more generally used to convey such ideas as love, happiness, and beauty. Also used as a pink accent color and in association with Hawaii and other Polynesian places and cultures. Google and Samsung's hibiscus flowers were previously orange.
Hibiscus was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: High-Heeled Shoe
description: A high-heeled shoe, primarily worn by women. Generally found in a context that requires formal dress, such as social occasions or some workplaces. Often used to represent fashion, glamour, or femininity, and appears frequently in posts about style or confidence (for example, â€˜slayingâ€™ a look). May also convey empowerment or sass, particularly within LGBTQ+ and drag culture. Displayed in red on most platforms, though the color has varied historically.
High-Heeled Shoe was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: High-Speed Train
description: A high speed train, designed to cover long distances at high speed. Can be used figuratively to show support for a cause or movement, inviting others to â€œget on boardâ€ with the ideaâ€”much like announcing â€œall aboard!â€ when a train is about to depart.
High-Speed Train was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: High Voltage
description: A symbol for high voltage , as warns against injury from electricity. Depicted as a jagged yellow bolt. Commonly used to represent lightning , electricity, and various flashes of light. Also widely used to represent metaphorical energy and signal attention online, and, as such, it can occasionally overlap with the ğŸ”¥ Fire emoji to symbolize excitement, excellence, or something that stands out. Samsungâ€™s bolt was previously white on a blue square, as an icon for high voltage.
High Voltage was approved as part of Unicode 4.0 in 2003 under the name "High Voltage Sign" and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Hiking Boot
description: A style of boot commonly worn on long walks or for hiking. Generally distinct from other footwear-related emojis by the considerable grip on the sole of the shoe.
Hiking Boot was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018 and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

name: Hindu Temple
description: A Hindu temple or mandir; a place of worship for followers of Hinduism. Depicted on most platforms as a red, orange, or golden building with a tall spire.
Hindu Temple was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Hippopotamus
description: A hippopotamus, a squat water mammal with huge jaws. Generally depicted in gray or tan in full profile facing left. Googleâ€™s design used to feature a purple, cartoon-styled hippopotamus face. Facebookâ€™s hippopotamus is opening massive jaws, revealing tusks.
Hippopotamus was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018 and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

name: Hole
description: A round, black, cartoon-styled hole, as a manhole or a hole (cup) in golf . May be used to represent various types of literal or figurative holes, e.g., black holes, rabbit holes.
Hole was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Hole

name: Hollow Red Circle
description: Used as an alternative to a check (tick) in Japan for a something that is correct. The opposite of an X ( cross mark ) for something wrong.
Hollow Red Circle was approved as part of Unicode 5.2 in 2009 under the name "Heavy Large Circle" and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Honey Pot
description: A golden-yellow pot of honey, as made by bees and desired by bears . Shown with the sweet substance oozing down its sides, often with a honey dipper inside the small vessel. May be used figuratively, as the term of endearment â€œhoney.â€ May also be used as sexual slang .
Honey Pot was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Honeybee
description: A honey bee, a busy, flying insect that lives in a hive and makes honey . Depicted as a black-and-yellow bee with clear or white wings and a stinger. Variously facing left in full profile or shown from above. May be used to represent various types of bees (e.g., bumblebee) and wasps (e.g., hornets, yellow jackets). May also be used to accent black-and-yellow colors or patterns. Popularly used in connection with singer and superstar BeyoncÃ© (nicknamed Queen Bey ) or for metaphorical queen bees . Can also be used to refer to the city of Manchester in the United Kingdom, as the worker bee is the symbol of the city.
Honeybee was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Hook
description: A gold or silver hook. Can be used to represent literal hooks like the kinds you use to crochet or catch fish. Also use metaphorically to talk about boxing or punching, music (the catchy part of a song), or in phrases like hook me up , hook up , getting hooked (on something) , or hook, line, and sinker .
Hook was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Horizontal Traffic Light
description: A set of red, orange (amber) and green traffic lights, used at intersections. Less common than the vertical traffic light . Similar in appearance to the traffic light controls in the upper-left of every OS X windows.
Horizontal Traffic Light was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Horse
description: A horse, a hoofed mammal used for riding and racing. Depicted as a brown horse in full profile galloping to the left, with a dark, flowing mane and tail. May be used to represent various types of horses and their metaphorical senses (e.g., mustang , stallion ). May also be used as a compliment to an attractive person. One of the 12 animals of the Chinese zodiac .a Not to be confused with ğŸ´ Horse Face , ğŸ  Carousel Horse , and ğŸ‡ Horse Racing , which features a jockey on its back. Appleâ€™s horse is wearing a green saddle blanket, Facebookâ€™s a blue blanket with saddle. SoftBankâ€™s design previously featured a racing horse with a jockey.

name: Horse Face
description: The face of a horse, generally facing left. Depicted as a light or reddish-brown horse with a dark brown or black mane, and, on many platforms, a light-colored muzzle. Not to be confused with the full-bodied ğŸ Horse or ğŸ‡ Horse Racing , though their applications may overlap. Some vendors implement a similar design in ğŸ¦„ Unicorn Face and ğŸ¦“ Zebra . WhatsAppâ€™s horse is facing left, as Facebookâ€™s previously was. Microsoftâ€™s horse was previously looking straight ahead, as was Samsungâ€™s , shown with a goofy, full-toothed grin. Softbank previously featured a full-bodied horse.
Horse Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Horse Racing
description: A jockey riding a horse in a race, shown riding to the left on most platforms. Can be used broadly to represent horse racing or equestrian sports, as well as the betting commonly associated with some of them. May also be used metaphorically to convey rushing, working quickly, or charging ahead (for example, â€˜racing through the dayâ€™).
Horse Racing was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Hospital
description: A place where people are taken to receive medical care. This hospital has a large red cross on the front, often used as a symbol for health care.
Hospital was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Hot Beverage
description: A cup of a steaming-hot beverage, usually taken as coffee or tea . Sometimes shown on a saucer. Samsung's design previously featured a foamy-white tulip latte art design. May be paired with the Frog Face to represent the snarky But That's None of My Business meme . Relatedly, can also be used alone to represent "tea" as per the slang phrase "spill the tea", used to request the sharing of gossip, news, or personal information. More recently, it can also be used to refer to a person's physical attractiveness, as per the slang phrase "your body is tea."
Hot Beverage was approved as part of Unicode 4.0 in 2003 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Hot Dog
description: The cooked sausage of a hot dog in a sliced bun and drizzled with yellow mustard, as eaten at a baseball game.
Hot Dog was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Hot Face
description: A reddish-orange face with furrowed eyebrows, tongue stuck out, and beads of sweat, as if overheated from high temperatures. Number and position of sweat droplets vary by platforms. May also represent physical attractiveness (slang, hot ). Most platforms feature expressions that are variations on ğŸ˜° Anxious Face With Sweat or ğŸ˜¥ Sad but Relieved Face .
Hot Face was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018 under the name "Overheated Face" and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

name: Hot Pepper
description: A bright red Mexican chili pepper, slightly curled and with a green stem. May be used to represent something â€œhot and spicy,â€ figuratively or literally, as a dish on a restaurant menu.
Hot Pepper was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Hot Pepper
description: A bright red Mexican chili pepper, slightly curled and with a green stem. May be used to represent something â€œhot and spicy,â€ figuratively or literally, as a dish on a restaurant menu.
Hot Pepper was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Hot Springs
description: Representation of hot springs with steam rising from a circular tub. This is the common symbol used to represent an onsen on maps in Japan . Outside its original context in Japan, this emoji has been known to be used to represent cooking steam, barbecue heat, or a stove.
Hot Springs was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Hot Springs

name: Hotel
description: A hotel building, displayed on most platforms as a building with many windows and a letter H on the front. Can be easily confused with the Love Hotel , or Hospital emoji. Microsoft previously depicted this emoji as a bed.
Hotel was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Hourglass Done
description: A classic hourglass, all of its sand having flowed into the bottom bulb. Indicates time has passed. Color varies across platforms. Commonly used for various content concerning time. May also be used for hourglass-shaped figures. Not to be confused with â³ Hourglass Not Done , whose sand is still flowing. Used on Snapchat to indicate a Snapstreak is soon to end.
Hourglass Done was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 under the name "Hourglass" and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Hourglass Not Done

Commonly used for various content concerning time. May also be used for hourglass-shaped figures. Not to be confused with âŒ› Hourglass Done , whose sand has stopped flowing.
Hourglass Not Done was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name "Hourglass with Flowing Sand" and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: House
description: A house, otherwise known as a home when someone is living in it. Suitable for a couple or larger family, other perhaps housemates. Distinct from an apartment building due to its detached form, this house is likely in the suburbs of a city or a rural area.
House was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name "House Building" and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: House with Garden

House with Garden was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Houses
description: Multiple houses near one another. May be used to discuss neighbourhoods, communities, or possibly real estate more broadly.
Houses was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 under the name "House Buildings" and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Houses

name: Hundred Points
description: 100 emoji: the number one-hundred, written in red, underlined twice for emphasis. Originating from the number 100 written on a school exam or paper to indicate a perfect score of 100 out of 100.  Teachers in Japan may also use a stamp in addition to the 100 mark, to indicate that a student has performed very well. This 100 emoji is commonly used as a shorthand for 100% , with the usage meaning â€œkeep it realâ€ or a similar sentiment. A 100 emoji can be used to express pride or general acceptance of an idea. This emoji is alluded to in the 2025 hit Netflix show Adolescence . Learn more here . In Snapchat , the 100 emoji appearing next to a fire emoji indicates a 100 day Snapstreak.
Hundred Points was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name "Hundred Points Symbol" and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Hushed Face
description: A yellow face with small, open eyes, raised eyebrows, and a small, open mouth, as if it has been hushed by concern or correction. Meaning widely varies, but its expression is commonly taken as surprise, embarrassment, or mild excitement. Similar to ğŸ˜² Astonished Face , which features larger eyes and mouth. Google previously interpreted hushed as "silenced," depicting the emoji with a zipper mouth until Android 6.0.1 . An early Microsoft design featured a face with closed eyes and a flat, closed mouth.
Hushed Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.1 in 2012 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Hut

Hut was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Hyacinth

Hyacinth was approved as part of Unicode 15.0 in 2022 and added to Emoji 15.0 in 2022.

name: Ice

In slang, ice refers to diamonds or expensive jewelry, while phrases like ice in my veins are used in sports contexts to describe being calm under pressure. Within the United States, this emoji has also been used as a visual stand-in for â€˜ICEâ€™ (Immigration and Customs Enforcement) in activist or protest posts.
Ice was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 under the name "Ice Cube" and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Ice Cream

Ice Cream was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Ice Hockey
description: A hockey stick and puck, used in the sport of ice hockey. Not to be confused with the field hockey stick and ball . Some hockey fans use this emoji to represent a â€œstick tap,â€ a form of applause where players tap their sticks to show respect, appreciation, or congratulations. As a result, its use may occasionally overlap with the ğŸ‘ Clapping Hands emoji.
Ice Hockey was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015 under the name "Ice Hockey Stick and Puck" and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Ice Skate

In the sport of figure skating, a white ice skate is traditionally worn by women, and a black ice skate is worn by men. This emoji doesn't define the color to be used, but no major vendor currently displays this as black.
Ice Skate was approved as part of Unicode 5.2 in 2009 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

Identification Card was approved as part of Unicode 14.0 in 2021 and added to Emoji 14.0 in 2021.

name: Inbox Tray
description: A paper tray with a down arrow on top, as a symbol for an email inbox. Generally depicted as a white or wooden try with a red arrow. Samsung and Twitter's arrows are green, WhatsApp's gray. May be used for various digital activity, including downloading, messaging, and emailing. Facebookâ€™s designs feature a yellow envelope angled forward and trailed by three, blue lines, indicating sending. Google's design also previously displayed as a yellow envelope. Appleâ€™s design previously featured three red motion lines, Microsoftâ€™s a rightwards arrow.
Incoming Envelope was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Index Pointing at the Viewer
description: A hand with the index finger pointing straight forward at the person viewing the emoji. Used to represent the word and concept of 'you,' the second-person singular and plural pronoun. This symbol is seen in art, advertisements, and military recruitment posters as a way to draw the viewer into the image they're looking at. This hand shape is also used in multiple sign languages from around the world.
Index Pointing at the Viewer was approved as part of Unicode 14.0 in 2021 and added to Emoji 14.0 in 2021.

name: Infinity
description: The symbol for infinity enclosed within a circle or square. Originally encoded as a symbol to represent acid-free paper , this permanent paper sign was later given emoji presentation to form an infinity emoji. May also be used by members of the autism rights movement to represent neurodiversity. Note: this emoji is not supported in Twitter / X names, to minimize confusion with a verified checkmark. Learn more here .
Infinity was approved as part of Unicode 4.1 in 2005 under the name "Permanent Paper Sign" and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

description: A lowercase letter i , enclosed in a rounded square or circle. Implemented in apps or websites to indicate that help or further information is available. May be used as a logo for tourist information signage in a town or city. Commonly used online to mean â€˜FYIâ€™ or to draw attention to a fact, detail, or announcement. Can also be used sarcastically to preface an unwanted truth.

name: Input Latin Letters
description: A symbol showing the lowercase letters a, b, c and d. Intended to be used on a software keyboard, or other input screen to enable alphabetical input, as opposed to numeric or symbol input.
Input Latin Letters was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name "Input Symbol for Latin Letters" and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Input Latin Lowercase
description: A symbol showing the lowercase letters a, b, c and d. Intended to be used on a software keyboard, or other input screen to toggle lowercase letter input.
Input Latin Lowercase was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name "Input Symbol for Latin Small Letters" and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Input Latin Uppercase
description: A symbol showing the capital letters A, B, C and D. Intended to be used on a software keyboard, or other input screen to toggle capital letter input.
Input Latin Uppercase was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name "Input Symbol for Latin Capital Letters" and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Input Numbers
description: A symbol showing the numbers 1, 2, 3 and 4. Intended to be used on a software keyboard, or other input screen to enable numeric input, as opposed to alphabetical or symbol input.
Input Numbers was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name "Input Symbol for Numbers" and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Jack-O-Lantern
description: An orange pumpkin carved into the shape of a face and commonly known as a Jack-oâ€™-lantern . The number and shape of its carved teeth vary by vendor. This emoji has consistently been the most popular emoji used to encapsulate Halloween during the month of October. This emoji predates the inclusion of emojis within Unicode . It was first added to early Japanese emoji keyboards in 2003 by au by KDDI .
Jack-O-Lantern was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Jar
description: An empty glass jar. May be used to talk about jars or anything that comes in jars, from pickles to condiments to jellies to sauces. This is an engagement tactic to help boost a postâ€™s reach, most commonly appearing on videos promoting charitable causes or fundraisers.
Jar was approved as part of Unicode 14.0 in 2021 and added to Emoji 14.0 in 2021.

name: Key
description: A key, as opens a door or lock . Depicted at a 45Â° angle as a gold, bronze, or copper key with a round head and notched blade. Commonly used for figurative senses of key , e.g., the key to success , being key ("crucial"). DJ Khaled uses the emoji to indicate his Snapchat stories are official (verified). Appleâ€™s design previously resembled a gold ğŸ—ï¸ Old Key , which emoji has similar applications. May also represent digital keys in public-key technology . Light Rail was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Light Skin Tone

Type 1 on the Fitzpatrick Scale of skin tones is described as: Pale white; blond or red hair; blue eyes; freckles Type 2 on the Fitzpatrick Scale of skin tones is described as: White; fair; blond or red hair; blue, green, or hazel eyes This is a combination of type 1 (pale white) and type 2 (white). Despite the descriptions, Appleâ€™s artwork tends to display this type-1-2 skin tone modifier with dark hair.
Light Skin Tone was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015 under the name "Emoji Modifier Fitzpatrick Type-1-2" and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

Lipstick was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Litter in Bin Sign
description: A symbol showing a person putting litter (rubbish) in the trash (rubbish bin). A more positive version of the Do Not Litter Symbol .
Litter in Bin Sign was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name "Put Litter in Its Place Symbol" and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Lizard
description: A lizard, a scaly reptile with a long tail. Depicted as a light-green lizard on all fours from above, generally looking left with large eyes, a lightly textured or colored back, and toes outspread, as a gecko . May be used for a variety of wild and pet lizards. Googleâ€™s lizard was previously brown.
Lizard was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

name: Llama
description: A llama, a long-necked, camel -like animal, native to South America and used for transport and wool. Depicted as a shaggy white, light-brown, or multicolored llama in full profile on all fours facing left. May be used to represent an alpaca or related animals.
Llama was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018 and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

name: Lobster
description: A lobster, a large crustacean with a prominent tail and pincers. Depicted as a reddish-orange lobster (as cooked) from above, with a long body and tail, short, tentacle-like eyes, and ten legs, the top of which are very large pincers. Often used to represent lobster as food as well as in connection to the US state of Maine. In its release year of 2018, Emojipediaâ€™s original sample image was criticized as anatomically incorrect but was shortly after resolved . That year, the transgender community embraced the lobster as a symbol for their efforts for Transgender Flag emoji. Samsung, WhatsApp, and Facebookâ€™s lobsters are depicted at an angle.
Lobster was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018 and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

name: Locomotive
description: A steam train, powered by coal or wood. An early type of locomotive, now mostly replaced by electric or diesel trains . May also be used figuratively to show support for a cause, trend, or movement, encouraging others to "get on board" with an idea, or to indicate that someone is joining the "hype train" or following a popular opinion or action.
Locomotive was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name "Steam Locomotive" and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Lollipop
description: A colorful lollipop made of swirled hard candy attached to a stick. Colors vary by platform, though most designs show rainbow colors or pinks and reds. This emoji tends to spike in use around Halloween . Samsung , Microsoft , and Facebook all used to have pink and red designs, but have since opted for rainbow colors.
Lollipop was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Long Drum
description: A long drum with a tall body and a cylindrical or hourglass shell. Can be used to represent various drums found around the world from Africa to the Caribbean to Latin America to Asia. Types of long drum include (but are not limited to) djembe, talking drum, conga, bongo, tumbadora, atabaque, and dhol. Can also be used to talk about drums, music, or beats in general.
Long Drum was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Lotion Bottle
description: A bottle of lotion for the skin, such as moisturizer or sunscreen (sunblock). May be used for other hygienic liquids, including shampoo and body wash , as well as beauty products. Appearance varies across platforms, but commonly depicted in white and gold colors. Some designs also include a droplet icon on the bottle. Most platforms feature a bottle with a pump, though others previously displayed a cylinder with a cap.
Lotion Bottle was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018 and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

name: Lotus

May convey inconsolable grief but also other intense feelings, such as uncontrollable laughter, pride or overwhelming joy. In March 2021, ğŸ˜­ Loudly Crying Face became the most popular emoji on Twitter . It held this position until January 2022, when ğŸ˜‚ Face with Tears of Joy returned as the top emoji on the platform .

Can also suggest shouting, excitement, or hype, and can occasionally be used to bookend words to mimic a loud or dramatic announcement.
Loudspeaker was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name "Public Address Loudspeaker" and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Melting Face
description: A yellow smiley face melting into a puddle. The eyes and mouth slip down the face, yet still maintain a distorted smile. This quality lends this emoji to sarcasm. Can be used literally to talk about extreme heat. Can also be used metaphorically to talk about embarrassment, shame, a slowly sinking sense of dread, or feeling overwhelmed in some way. Google's original design for this emoji was featured on the cover of The New York Times in September 2021.
Melting Face was approved as part of Unicode 14.0 in 2021 and added to Emoji 14.0 in 2021.

name: Metro
description: A metro: frequent underground train found in built-up areas with high populations. This emoji is generally displayed as a forward-facing train, with some platforms also displaying a tunnel as a circle surrounding the train. Apple's artwork shows the characters IL2 which may be a reference to one of the more locked-down buildings at Apple's Infinite Loop Headquarters during iPhone development (IL2 = Infinite Loop 2).
Metro was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Microbe
description: A microbe, as a bacterium grown in a ğŸ§« Petri Dish or observed under a ğŸ”¬ Microscope . Generally depicted as a squiggly, single-celled microorganism with prominent cilia . Color, shape, and position vary across platforms. Commonly used to represent bacteria, viruses, and germs and disease more generally. In 2020, this emoji became primarily used in reference to Coronavirus / COVID-19 . Apple's version of this emoji most closely represents a virus, while others from Samsung, Microsoft and Twitter appear as bright green bacteria. Other versions of this emoji also appear mainly as bacteria: Facebook's is indigo, and WhatsAppâ€™s purple. Googleâ€™s design previously displayed five microbes in different, bright colors.
Microbe was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018 and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

name: Microphone
description: A microphone, used to amplify a personâ€™s voice when speaking or singing. Previously shown with music notes on most platforms, implying it to be used for a singer / singing. Today only Twitter's design retains these notes.
Microphone was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Microscope
description: A microscope, as used in science laboratories to magnify small objects, such as cells or insects . Depicted as a compound opitical microscope with an adjustable eyepiece, lens, arm, and slide stage mounted on a base. Generally shown as metal with the viewing apparatus facing left. Commonly used for various content concerning science and research. May also be used for various senses of inspection (e.g., taking a closer took). Googleâ€™s design was previously shown in red.
Microscope was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Military Helmet
description: A round military helmet with a chinstrap. All platforms depict a green helmet, with some designs featuring a green camouflage pattern.

name: Military Medal
description: A ribbon and medallion, generally awarded to a person in the military for heroic acts. Can also be used to represent achievements, awards, or recognition more broadly, including in gaming contexts.
Military Medal was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Military Medal
description: A ribbon and medallion, generally awarded to a person in the military for heroic acts. Can also be used to represent achievements, awards, or recognition more broadly, including in gaming contexts.
Military Medal was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Milky Way
description: The Milky Way â€“ a galaxy of billions of stars that includes our own solar system and planet earth . Shown by many platforms as a night sky, with silhouettes of mountains or hills in the foreground.
Milky Way was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Minibus
description: A small bus or minivan designed to carry fewer people than a full-sized bus . Displayed in white on most platforms, though it is green on Facebook.
Minibus was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Minus
description: A large minus symbol, as used in mathematics.
Minus was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name "Heavy Minus Sign" and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Mirror
description: A mirror with an ornate gold or silver frame. The shape and style of the mirror varies from platform to platform. Used to talk about mirrors, reflection, or self-reflection.
Mirror was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Mirror Ball
description: A mirror ball, also called a disco ball. A hanging sphere made up of a bunch of tiny mirrors, which reflect spots of light around a room, creating a party atmosphere. Often used by Swifties to reference Taylor Swift's 2020 song mirrorball .
Mirror Ball was approved as part of Unicode 14.0 in 2021 and added to Emoji 14.0 in 2021.

name: Moai
description: A moai , one of the famed, giant stone statues of human figures on Easter Island. Depicted as a gray stone carving of a stylized human head with a prominent brow and nose, most often facing left. Sometimes used for various idiosyncratic purposes, such as conveying a stoic, deadpan, or silly expression. For example, this emoji is often used to represent various "sigma" or "chad" memes due to its chiselled emotionaless features. Its official Unicode name of Moyai and inclusion in early Japanese emoji sets, such as from au by KDDI, suggest the emoji may represent the Moyai Statue near Shibuya Station in Tokyo, Japan; previous designs from Google and Microsoft resemble the Tokyo statue. Other Tokyo landmarks are represented in ğŸ—¼ Tokyo Tower and, formerly, Shibuya 109 .
Moai was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name "Moyai" and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Mobile Phone
description: A mobile phone (cell phone), as used to text, check social media, or take selfies . Depicted as a black or gray smartphone with a generic blue screen or multicolored app icons. Commonly used for various content concerning mobile phones, technology, and communication. The designs from Apple, Google, Microsoft, and Samsung resemble phones offered by their respective companies, e.g., iPhone. WhatsAppâ€™s design features a night sky as its wallpaper, displaying the time as 9:34. Early designs for the mobile phone emoji from au by KDDI resembled a traditional telephone receiver , and vice versa, before having their codepoints swapped in later releases. See also ğŸ“² Mobile Phone With Arrow .
Mobile Phone was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Mobile Phone Off
description: A sign indicating that mobile phones should be turned off. Used in situations such as a cinema or live performance. Displayed as a mobile phone with the word OFF. Previously shown with a cross instead of the word OFF on Windows .
Mobile Phone Off was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Mobile Phone with Arrow
description: A mobile phone (cell phone) with a rightward arrow pointed at it from the left. Intended to indicate an incoming call or message, but used to represent mobile phones, technology, and communication more generally. Arrow color varies, but is often blue. Vendors implement the same design as ğŸ“± Mobile Phone .
Mobile Phone with Arrow was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name "Mobile Phone with Rightwards Arrow at Left" and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Money-Mouth Face
description: A yellow face with raised eyebrows, currency symbols for eyes (usually dollar signs ), and an open smile sticking out a tongue (usually colored green with a dollar sign , echoing a dollar banknote ). Facebook's design shows this emoji's dollar sign eyes over a gray coin shape, while Huawei's emoji design has yen-shaped eyes instead of dollar signs . Used for a wide range of content dealing with money, including making money, loving wealth, being or feeling rich, and concepts of success and excellence (e.g., on the money ).
Money-Mouth Face was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Money Bag
description: A bag full of money. Depicted as a sack, usually tan, tied off and displaying a dollar sign . May be filled with coins, as most platforms show a rounded bag. Commonly used for various content concerning wealth and money.
Money Bag was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Money with Wings
description: A banded stack of U.S. dollar bills with feather wings, as if flying. Its flight may represent losing, transferring, or earning money, but commonly used for wealth, money, and success more generally, often with a flourish or sense of flair.
Money with Wings was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Monkey
description: A monkey, a small primate with long limbs and tail for climbing trees. Generally depicted as a cartoon-styled, brown monkey with a cheeky facial expression, shown in full profile facing left, sitting on its hind legs with a long, curled tail and round ears. As with ğŸµ Monkey Face , often used with a playful tone or for metaphorical senses of monkey . One of the 12 animals of the Chinese zodiac . WhatsAppâ€™s monkey is facing right, Facebookâ€™s has shaggy hair. This emoji is considered racist in some contexts , particularly when used to disparage, insult, and abuse people with dark skin, especially Black people.
Monkey was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Monkey Face
description: A friendly, cartoon-styled face of a monkey, looking straight ahead. Depicted as a brown-haired monkey with a tan or pinkish face, round ears, nostrils, and open-mouthed grin. As with the full-bodied ğŸ’ Monkey , often used with a playful tone or for metaphorical senses of monkey . One of the 12 animals of the Chinese zodiac . Available as an Apple Animoji . Vendors implement the same or similar monkey face in their Three Wise Monkeys emojis: ğŸ™ˆ See-No-Evil Monkey , ğŸ™‰ Hear-No-Evil Monkey , and ğŸ™Š Speak-No-Evil Monkey . Facebookâ€™s monkey previously resembled ğŸ» Bear Face . This emoji is considered racist in some contexts , particularly when used to disparage, insult, and abuse people with dark skin, especially Black people.
Monkey Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Monorail
description: Similar to a train , but running on a single track. Monorails are often found at theme parks , or other tourist destinations. According to the designers , Facebook's design for this emoji drew inspiration from the Disneyland monorail .
Monorail was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Moon Cake
description: The round, golden-brown pastry of a Chinese mooncake, a traditional delicacy and lunar symbol of the Mid-Autumn Festival . Many platforms feature a design or character imprinted on the crust, and depict a slice cut out to show a brown paste with a duck egg yolk inside. Twitter displays the Chinese character for â€œfall/autumnâ€ or â€œharvestâ€ (ç§‹) on top.
Moon Cake was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018 and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

name: Moon Viewing Ceremony
description: Moon Viewing Ceremonies (called Tsukimi in Japan) are held each year in autumn to celebrate the full moon and waxing moon in Japan. This symbol shows Japanese pampas grass and dango (sweet dessert food) which are used in the ceremony, as well as the moon in the background.
Moon Viewing Ceremony was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Moose
description: A moose head with large antlers. Can be used to talk about the actual animal. Can also be used to represent countries, including Canada and Sweden, where the moose is considered a national symbol. Can also be used alongside the phrase "cool as a moose." Googleâ€™s Moose is facing left, while Twitter displays a full-bodied moose.
Moose was approved as part of Unicode 15.0 in 2022 and added to Emoji 15.0 in 2022.

name: Mosque
description: A mosque building, a place of worship for followers of Islam . Shown with a domed roof and a minaret .
Mosque was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Mosquito
description: A mosquito, a type of bloodsucking fly. Depicted as a brown or black mosquito on its six, long legs, with wings, long abdomen, and needle-like mouth. Variously shown from above or facing left. May be used to represent various insects, other bugs and bug bites, and insect-borne diseases (e.g., malaria ). May also be used for metaphorical pests . Facebookâ€™s mosquito has a red abdomen, as if filled with blood .
Mosquito was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018 and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

name: Motor Boat
description: A small boat powered by an engine. Also known as a speedboat or powerboat. May be used for sexual slang .
Motor Boat was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Motor Boat
description: A small boat powered by an engine. Also known as a speedboat or powerboat. May be used for sexual slang .
Motor Boat was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Motor Scooter
description: A motor scooter, which may be displayed as any type of motorbike with or without a step-through frame. Distinct from the racing motorcycle , which is used for sport, not transport.
Motor Scooter was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

name: Motorcycle
description: A motorcycle, otherwise known as a motorbike used for sport/racing purposes. For a transport-based motorcycle, use a motor scooter.
Motorcycle was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 under the name "Racing Motorcycle" and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Motorcycle

Motorcycle was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 under the name "Racing Motorcycle" and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Motorway
description: A wide road, shown from a first-person perspective. Usually shown with an overhead gantry sign providing directional guidance, though some vendors show a roadside route confirmation sign instead. Apple's artwork displays a road sign to Curpertino , the city in California where the company is headquartered. Microsoft and Skype previously showed a sun on the horizon.
Motorway was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Mount Fuji
description: Mount Fuji (called Fuji-san in Japan) is the tallest mountain in Japan. Often seen with snow on the peak in colder months of the year. Occasionally used to reference broad Japanese cultural themes, including by those vacationing in the country, but can also be used generally to represent mountains or scenic landscapes. Similar to â›°ï¸ Mountain and ğŸ”ï¸ Snow-Capped Mountain , it can also be used metaphorically to represent ambition, stability, or perseverance. name: Mountain

name: Mouse
description: Eek! A mouse, a small rodent with large ears and a long tail. Generally depicted in white in full profile on all fours facing left, with pink ears, feet, and tail, often with reddish eyes. See also ğŸ­ Mouse Face . Not to be confused with ğŸ€ Rat or ğŸ–±ï¸ Computer Mouse . Facebookâ€™s mouse is sitting on its hind legs. name: Mouse Trap
description: A trap used to catch a mouse , rat , or other unwanted rodent. Metaphorically used in emoji form to suggest any kind of trap or entrapment. The style of trap shown on major platforms has a box held high with a single stick. A wedge of cheese is used to lure a mouse into the box, knocking the stick away and trapping â€” but not killing â€” the mouse. This is distinct from other traps which kill or injure upon capture.
Mouse Trap was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Mouth
description: A human mouth which is generally displayed as a pair of lips and a top row of teeth, instead of the inside of the mouth. name: Movie Camera
description: A classic movie camera. Depicted as a black camera with two mounted reels of film , viewfinder, and lens pointed left or right. Commonly used for various content concerning movies, film, and video as well as an icon for a video, as before an upload, link, or credit. May also be used in relation to the 2017 Emoji Movie . Facebookâ€™s design previously resembled a video camera mounted on a tripod. Not to be confused with ğŸ“½ï¸ Film Projector .

name: Multiply
description: A large multiplication symbol, as used in mathematics.

name: Mushroom
description: The fungus of the mushroom, depicted as a toadstool with a white-spotted red cap and stem. This design resembles the fly agaric mushroom (Amanita muscaria), a well-known species recognized in fairy tales, fantasy art, and video games (such as the Super Mario series). Can be used to discuss mushrooms broadly, though the ğŸ„â€ğŸŸ« Brown Mushroom emoji was introduced in 2023 to more accurately represent edible mushrooms.  This was due to most red-and-white mushrooms being poisonous. Can also be used in reference to magical concoctions or psychedelics.
Mushroom was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Musical Keyboard
description: A small section of a music keyboard, which differs from a computer keyboard . Showing white and black keys, this keyboard is played by a pianist to make music . Commonly used as a piano emoji.
Musical Keyboard was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Musical Note
description: A music note emoji, which can denote song lyrics, or other music related topics. Displays as two eighth-notes ( quavers in British English) connected with a beam. A single eight-note ( quaver ) was previously used in Microsoft and Googleâ€™s emoji designs.
Musical Note was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Musical Notes

Musical Notes was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name "Multiple Musical Notes" and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Musical Score
description: A staff (or stave) showing a treble clef and five horizontal lines.
Musical Score was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Muted Speaker
description: A speaker with a red line through it, indicating muted volume or silencing of audio.
Muted Speaker was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name "Speaker with Cancellation Stroke" and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Nail Polish
description: Colored nail polish being applied to fingernails. While it can be used literally in posts about beauty, glamour, or self-care, this emoji is most widely recognized for conveying confidence, sass, and a sense of nonchalance or indifference. Shown as red, pink, or purple nail polish on most platforms, the color rarely changes the meaning of this emoji. Previously displayed as a single bottle of nail polish on Android and on Windows .
Nail Polish was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

Name Badge was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: National Park
description: A national park, generally displayed with mountains , a river or stream, and trees . Most often used in posts about nature, hiking, or travel. May also suggest peace, escape, or appreciation for natural beauty.
National Park was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Nauseated Face
description: A sickly-green face with concerned eyes and puffed, often red cheeks, as if holding back vomit. May represent physical illness or general disgust. Not to be confused with ğŸ¤® Face Vomiting . Differs from other smileys conveying sickness, including ğŸ¤’ Face With Thermometer (used especially for colds and flus) and ğŸ¤• Face With Head-Bandage (physical injury).
Nauseated Face was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

name: Nazar Amulet
description: A nazar , an eye-shaped amulet believed to protect against the evil eye , especially in Turkish culture. Depicted as a rich blue, circular bead with a black dot in the center ringed with white and light blue, resembling an eye . Commonly used to represent eyes, various senses of looking, various senses of charms, envy and jealousy, and Turkey and Turkish culture. Also used for its blue color more generally. WhatsApp, Facebook, and Huawei's designs include a small hole, as for threading the amulet on a string or chain. Note: this emoji is not supported in Twitter / X names, to minimize confusion with a verified checkmark. Learn more here .
Nazar Amulet was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018 and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

name: Necktie
description: A necktie commonly worn at work or formal occasions, usually shown being worn with a shirt. Colors and patterns for both the necktie and the shirt vary by platform. Previous designs from Google , Facebook , and Samsung displayed a necktie on its own.
Necktie was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Nerd Face
description: A smiling yellow face with glasses, often with teeth showing, originally buck teeth on most platforms. While this emoji is often used by people calling themselves nerds in a self-deprecating way, the nerdy glasses paired with buck teeth can, and often does, evoke anti-Asian stereotypes. The fact that the default color of emoji faces is yellow further pushes this emoji into racist " yellowface " territory. Some platforms have redesigned nerd face over time to not have buck teeth, perhaps in acknowledgement of the harm this imagery may cause. Google, Facebook, WhatsApp, and JoyPixels originally featured designs with buck teeth but have since changed (or completely removed) the teeth on nerd face . Apple, Twitter, Microsoft, Samsung, and other platforms still use designs for this emoji that include buck teeth.
Nerd Face was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Nest with Eggs
description: A bird's nest with eggs inside. May be used to talk about actual nests or birds. May also be used to talk about home in general or to represent phrases like nest egg or empty nest . ğŸª¹ Empty Nest was approved at the same time as Nest with Eggs .
Nest with Eggs was approved as part of Unicode 14.0 in 2021 and added to Emoji 14.0 in 2021.

name: Nesting Dolls
description: Nesting dolls, also called matryoshka dolls or Russian dolls, decorated with bright colors including red, yellow, blue, and green. All platforms depict the nesting dolls as open, revealing smaller dolls within the bases of larger dolls. Dolls are all decorated with women wearing headscarfs. Some platforms show a flower motif on the women's dresses or aprons.
Nesting Dolls was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Neutral Face

Neutral Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: New Moon

May be used to represent the moon more generally, nighttime, outer space, and astronomy. May also be used to convey enchanting or eerie feelings. See also ğŸŒš New Moon Face . New Moon was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name "New Moon Symbol" and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

description: A bicycle with a red stroke through it, indicating that bikes are prohibited from this location. May be seen in pedestrian malls with a bicycle restriction or crossing train tracks in some countries.

No Littering was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name "Do Not Litter Symbol" and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

Google's design includes the text "under" above the number eighteen. The Samsung version of this emoji previously displayed the number 19 . This may have been due to the practice of counting the first year of life as one instead of zero in parts of East Asia such as South Korea (the location of the Samsung Headquarters).
No One Under Eighteen was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name "No One Under Eighteen Symbol" and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Notebook
description: A dark-colored, hardcover notebook, as used to write or take notes in school. Commonly used for various content concerning writing and schooling. Several platforms, including Apple, feature a cover with black-and-white marbling, evoking a classic composition book used in the U.S. Apple's design displays Notes on its cover. Google , Microsoft , and Samsungâ€™s covers were previously yellow or brown.

name: People Hugging
description: Two people hugging, shown as faceless blue or grey forms on most platforms. Details of each person are not distinct and thus no options are available to customize the gender or skin tone of either individual. Not to be confused with ğŸ¤— Hugging Face , which is less clearly a representation of hugging and sometimes used as jazz hands or to express excitement. Has been known to be confused for a ğŸ¥ Movie Camera emoji when displayed at small sizes, owing to similarities in shape and color.
People Hugging was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: People with Bunny Ears
description: An iteration of the Playboy Bunny known in Japan as a Bunny Girl . Usually depicted as an attractive woman  wearing bunny ears; a bunny girl can also be seen in anime as a hybrid human/animal known as Kemonomimi . Some versions of this emoji, such as Appleâ€™s, display two girls dancing, each wearing a leotard and bunny ears. Other interpretations show the face of one woman wearing bunny ears. The two-person version of this emoji is often used as a display of friendship, fun, or "let's party".
People with Bunny Ears was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name "Women with Bunny Ears" and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Person Bowing
description: A person bowing deeply, which is known as dogeza in Japan. Generally used to express a sincere apology or to request a large favour. It can also be used in a self-deprecating manner to express embarrassment or, due to the person's positioning, convey exhaustion. In some cultures and religious contexts, this emoji may also be used as a sign of prayer or worship. Earlier designs led some users to misinterpret this emoji as showing a person doing push-ups, lying down for a massage, or doing a cute "head resting on hands" gesture. While it may be used in these ways infrequently, its most common meanings are those of apology and respect.
Person Bowing was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name "Person Bowing Deeply" and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

description: A person swinging a golf club, attempting to hit a golf ball toward the flag on the green . Usually used to represent the sport of golf and related activities. By extension, it can also serve as shorthand for wealth, luxury, or retirement. May be used more figuratively to suggest â€˜taking a swing at something,â€™ meaning giving something a try or making an attempt, even if the outcome is uncertain. Conversely, it can also reference getting a 'hole in one,' implying a perfectly executed action or an ideal result. It can also be used figuratively for â€˜shooting your shot,â€™ meaning to make a bold or risky move, often in a flirty context.

name: Person in Bed
description: A bed with a gender-unspecified person sleeping in it, as at a house , hotel , hostel, or other sleeping accommodation. Used especially for various content concerning sleeping as well as beds, furniture, housing, relaxing, and other bedroom activities. Shown with a headboard at the left and footboard with a person under the covers, head on the pillow. Most platforms suggest a wooden frame and feature blue or red sheets. The appearance of the person varies. Apple and Facebook's designs show only the hair of the sleeper, Apple's black and Facebook's brown and tousled. Other major vendors show the head of the sleeper in default yellow with short, brown or blonde hair. Skin tone support is not recommended for this emoji, though it is supported on some platforms . Vendors implement the same style of bed as for their ğŸ›ï¸ Bed , but with a sleeper in it.
Person in Bed was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 under the name "Sleeping Accommodation" and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

description: A baked dish with a pastry crust, filled with sweet or savory ingredients. Appearance widely varies by platform. Apple depicts a whole pie in a tin, its crimped crust scored to let out steam. WhatsApp and Twitter's designs depict a slice of cherry pie. Google's design previously showed a slice of pumpkin pie, as served at Thanksgiving .
Pie was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017 and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

name: Pig
description: A pig, a plump animal farmed for its meat, such as bacon . Depicted in light pink in full profile on all fours facing left, with a long snout and short, curly tail. May be used to represent the animal, its food products, or various metaphorical senses of pig . As such, it can be used to describe someone as gluttonous or messy. One of the 12 animals of the Chinese zodiac ; 2019 is the Year of the Pig. See also ğŸ· Pig Face , ğŸ½ Pig Nose , and ğŸ— Boar . WhatsAppâ€™s design previously featured a wide grin.
Pig was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Pig Face
description: A friendly, cartoon-styled face of a pig looking straight ahead. Depicted as a pink face with a neutral expression, pointed or floppy ears, and a distinctive pig nose . Often used with a more affectionate tone than the full-bodied ğŸ– Pig . However, it can also be used metaphorically to describe someone as gluttonous or messy. Available as an Apple Animoji . Appleâ€™s face bears a slight grin and previously featured floppy ears.
Pig Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Pig Nose
description: The snout of a pig. Depicted as a pink oval or slightly pear-shaped nose with two black nostrils. Like ğŸ– Pig and ğŸ· Pig Face , it may be used metaphorically to describe someone as gluttonous or messy. Previously displayed as a cute pig character on Google Gmail .

name: Pile of Poo
description: A swirl of brown poop, shaped like soft-serve ice cream with large, excited eyes and frequently a big, friendly smile . Widely agreed to have been inspired by the various poop-shaped characters within the Dr. Slump manga series by Akira Toriyama. May be used to represent feces and other bathroom topics as well as stand in for their many related slang terms. It also enjoys a wide range of idiosyncratic applications, such as conveying a sense of whimsy or silliness, given its fun, happy expression. Microsoft and Google previously depicted a literal pile of feces, Googleâ€™s design featuring stink lines and flies hovering above it. Available as an Apple Animoji . This emoji predates the inclusion of emojis within Unicode . It was first added to early Japanese emoji keyboards by Softbank in 1997 .
Pile of Poo was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

It is in this context that this emoji is possibly alluded to in the 2025 hit Netflix show Adolescence . Learn more here .
