name: Pinched Fingers
description: An emoji showing the fingers held together in a vertical orientation, often referred to as the Italian hand gesture ma che vuoi , sometimes called the "finger purse." In Italy this gesture tends to be used in disagreement, frustration, or disbelief and can mean â€œWhat do you want?â€ or â€œWhat are you saying?â€ Outside Italy anyone performing a caricature of an Italian person, regardless of context or tone, might use this gesture. Pinched Fingers has a variety of other culturally specific uses. In Israeli culture it can mean â€œhold on,â€ â€œrelax,â€ or â€œbe patient.â€ The K-Pop star Yuri uses it as a signature gesture to represent a dumpling and a general warm sentiment. It can also be used to represent the act of fisting . Not to be confused with ğŸ¤ Pinching Hand , which has overlapping senses. Both are used to represent precision when someone is making a sharp point with accompanying speech.
Pinched Fingers was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Placard
description: A sign on a post, commonly used to promote ideas, causes, or make announcements. Often used used in the context of politics to represent a lawn sign or a poster brought to a protest. Also seen in commercial advertising. Shown with indiscernible writing or not writing at all, this emoji is flexible in its use. WhatsApp shows a peace sign, which tilts the meaning away from commercial use.

name: Place of Worship
description: A building used for worship by people of any faith or religion. Examples include a church , mosque , or synagogue . A person is shown on their knees praying, in this symbol. Multi-faith places of worship are commonly found at airports .
Place of Worship was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Play Button
description: A triangle-shaped arrow, pointing right. Commonly used as a symbol for play. See the glossary for information on the term black in unicode character names.

name: Playground Slide
description: A slide with a ladder, as seen in children's playgrounds. May be used to talk about children, parks, or playtime. May also be used metaphorically to talk about a smooth movement or action like the popular dance the electric slide or sliding into someone's DMs, usually for the purpose of flirting. Additionally may be used in reference to something with a downward descent.
Playground Slide was approved as part of Unicode 14.0 in 2021 and added to Emoji 14.0 in 2021.

name: Pleading Face
description: A yellow face with furrowed eyebrows, a small frown, and large, â€œpuppy dogâ€ eyes, as if begging, pleading, or yearning (possibly even in a NSFW manner, depending on the context). May also represent adoration or feeling touched by a loving gesture. Huawei's design for this emoji includes a pair of ğŸ™ Folded Hands . At its peak the Pleading Face was the third most popular emoji used on Twitter , and was the most commonly found emoji in tweets that include hearts . name: Plunger

Plunger was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Plus

name: Poodle
description: A poodle , a popular dog breed with curly hair, often groomed in an ornamental pattern. Generally depicted as a grayish-white poodle in full profile on all fours facing left, with a shaved torso, legs, and face with fuller, pom-pom-like hair on its head, ears, chest, feet, and tip of tail (as the Continental Clip ). Like ğŸ• Dog , may be used to represent a variety of dog breeds (often fluffy or long-haired). See also ğŸ¶ Dog Face . Google , Samsung , and Facebookâ€™s designs previously featured pink poodles.
Poodle was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Pool 8 Ball
description: This emoji displays the black 8 ball on most platforms, which looks similar to the Magic 8-Ball toy. This is despite the fact that emoji was originally created intending to represent game of billiards, of which pool is a common version. Samsung previously displayed this emoji with a cue and triangular arrangement of colored balls, as did Google and Microsoft (sans cue).
Pool 8 Ball was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name "Billiards" and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Popcorn
description: The buttery-white snack of popcorn brimming in a classic red-and-white-striped carton, as enjoyed at a movie theater . May be used to express engagement (â€œedge of oneâ€™s seatâ€).
Popcorn was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Post Office
description: A European-style post office. A postal horn can be seen on the front, which is commonly found in the logos of European Postal Services .
Post Office was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name "European Post Office" and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Postal Horn
description: A postal horn (post horn). Depicted as a coiled, valveless, brass horn, like a bugle or trumpet , with two red tassels. Sometimes used to mark announcements as well as for various content concerning brass instruments, music, or mail. In the 18â€“19th centuries, post horns signaled the arrival of and cleared the way for mail coaches, like a modern-day siren . Used today as a symbol on postboxes (mailboxes) and by many European postal services, as seen featured in ğŸ¤ European Post Office .
Postal Horn was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Postbox
description: A postbox (mailbox, letterbox) with a letter in its slot for collection. Generally depicted in red with a white envelope, styled after public postboxes in Japan . May also evoke postboxes in the United Kingdom . Used for various content concerning postal deliveries and email . Microsoftâ€™s design was previously blue, after U.S. mail collection boxes.
Postbox was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Pot of Food
description: A pot, as a casserole dish, filled with a warm and hearty beef or vegetable stew on most platforms. Generally used for eating and cooking (â€œa mealâ€), and commonly associated with soup or Japanese nabe . Samsungâ€™s design previously resembled a bowl of ramen or other noodle dish, with chopsticks .
Pot of Food was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Potable Water
description: A symbol for potable (drinkable) water, usually shown with a faucet filling a drinking glass. Commonly used for various content concerning water, drinking, thirst, and dripping. Some platforms, including Apple and WhatsApp, depict the emoji as an object while others feature a stylized, white faucet on a blue square, as a sign or icon of water that is safe to drink. Compare ğŸš± Non-Potable Water , which indicates water that is not safe to drink. Apple's design previously featured a blue symbol design, Microsoft's a cup filled with water.
Potable Water was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name "Potable Water Symbol" and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Potato
description: A whole potato, such as a russet, used for baking, mashing, or frying, shown with a few eyes on its golden-brown skin. Not to be confused with the roasted sweet potato , though their uses may overlap. May be used as an insult, either to disparage a person based on their appearance or perceived lack of intelligence, or to decry low-quality digital content, including blurry images, distorted audio, or pixelated video. Can be used to reference a mash-up in music , though this use case is uncommon.
Potato was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016.

name: Potted Plant
description: A leafy green plant in pot. Plant type varies by platform. Occasionally used as slang for marijuana.
Potted Plant was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Poultry Leg
description: A crispy brown leg (drumstick) of chicken , duck , turkey , or other poultry on the bone, as roasted at Thanksgiving or Christmas dinner or fried at fast-food restaurants. Often used to broadly represent poultry-based foods, most frequently chicken wings, nuggets, or tenders. Relatedly, this emoji may be used to reference the financial slang term â€œtendies,â€ a playful expression for investment gains. This emoji can also be considered racist in some contexts, particularly when used to disparage, insult, and abuse people with dark skin, especially Black people.
Poultry Leg was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Pound Banknote
description: Quids in! A banded stack of pound banknotes, the paper currency of the United Kingdom ( England , Wales , Northern Ireland , and Scotland ). Color and detail vary across platforms, but widely depicted as purple Â£20 notes with the pound sign, Â£. Commonly used for various content concerning wealth and money, not restricted to the U.K. Samsung's design displays Â£10 notes.
Pound Banknote was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name "Banknote with Pound Sign" and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Pouring Liquid
description: A glass pouring liquid. May be used to represent the literal act of pouring. May also be used to represent ritual libations or to honor the dead by pouring out a drink in a person's memory.
Pouring Liquid was approved as part of Unicode 14.0 in 2021 and added to Emoji 14.0 in 2021.

description: A string of beads, as used in prayer or meditation in many religious traditions . Generally depicted as red, wooden beads with a gold, decorative center bead and tassel. Commonly used to represent various religious sentiments, jewelry, and magic. Samsung previously featured a Latin cross , suggesting a Christian rosary , though now joins other vendor designs in resembling an Islamic misbaha or Buddhist mala .
Prayer Beads was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Printer
description: A computer printer, as at a home office. Generally depicted as a grayish device with a power button and paper loaded in its tray, sometimes printing out a document. May be used for various content concerning printing, including as a Print icon, as well as for office work and technology more generally. Not to be confused with ğŸ“  Fax Machine .
Printer was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Prohibited
description: A red circle with a diagonal line through the middle, from top-left to bottom right, used to indicate that something is not permitted Commonly shown in conjunction with other symbols to indicate No Smoking , No Bikes , or similar.
Prohibited was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name "No Entry Sign" and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Purple Circle
description: A circle shown in the color of purple. May be used to represent anything purple. During 2024 this emoji began to be used by French users of social media platforms to reference a term for a serious form of assault. This was due to its phonetic similarity to the color purple within the French language. Additionally, as with other color-based shape emojis (most notably the hearts ), this emoji may also used to express an affinity with or appreciation for various people, places, groups, objects, or ideas associated with the same color.
Purple Circle was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 under the name "Large Purple Circle" and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Purple Heart
description: A purple heart emoji, often used alongside other colored hearts . As with the other color-based hearts, this emoji is often also used to express an affinity with or appreciation for various people, places, groups, objects, or ideas associated with the same color. For example, this emoji is frequently used on Twitter/X in reference to the Korean boy band Bangtan Sonyeondan , more commonly known as BTS. May also be used in reference to the Purple Heart (PH) medal in the U.S. military for soldiers killed or wounded in combat. This emoji is mentioned in the 2025 hit Netflix show Adolescence . Learn more here . Previously shown as a pink heart in Android 4.4 .
Purple Heart was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Purple Square
description: A square shown in the color of purple. May be used to represent anything purple.
Purple Square was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 under the name "Large Purple Square" and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Purse
description: A small pouch with a clasp, generally used to hold coins. Sometimes called a â€œcoin purse.â€ Color varies by platform, though most platforms have a pink, blue, or turquoise bag with a silver or gold (gray or yellow) clasp. Not to be confused with ğŸ‘ Clutch Bag , which can look like a coin person on some platforms, due to lack of relative scale in emoji designs.
Purse was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Pushpin
description: A thumbtack (drawing pin), as used to pin documents on a bulletin (notice) board. Depicted at a 45Â° angle with its red, flat head to the upper right. Often used as an icon for Pinterest or metaphorically pinning content online. Not to be confused with ğŸ“ Round Pushpin , though their applications may overlap.

name: Red Heart
description: A classic red love heart emoji. The red heart ideograph is traditionally used for expressions of love and romance across many cultures, with this being amongst the most frequence use cases for this emoji. However, the Red Heart emoji is also often used to express non-romantic positive sentiments, in part thanks to its use as one of the default reaction emoji options across many social messaging platforms (e.g. Instagram , Slack , WhatsApp ). Additionally, as with the other color-based hearts, this emoji is often also used to express an affinity with or appreciation for various people, places, groups, objects, or ideas associated with the same color. This is historically the most popular heart emoji by a considerable distance and is amongst the most popular emojis of all time. A similar emoji exists for the heart suit in a deck of playing cards. On Snapchat , this emoji displays next to a friend when you have been #1 BFs with each other for two consecutive weeks. Note: the Unicode Character Database (UCD) name â€œHeavy Black Heartâ€ pre-dates color emoji, when the term referred to a solid, black â¤ï¸ heart character. See the glossary for information on the term black in historic Unicode character names.
Red Heart was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 under the name "Heavy Black Heart" and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Shaking Face
description: A face that appears to be shaking from side to side with its eyes and mouth open wide. This emoji finds its origins in the comic book and cartoon trope of a shaking face. name: Sport Utility Vehicle

This emoji goes back to the late 1990s when it was included in Docomo's emoji set . In 2009, it appeared on a proposal as one of many symbols available on Japanese phones recommended to be encoded into the Unicode Standard. In that proposal, the symbol was referred to as a "recreational vehicle" or RV. The original Japanese emojis look more like station wagons or SUVs than RVs. At various points, platforms including Google and Samsung showed this emoji as an RV, but ultimately the designs across platforms converged to a car that looks more like an SUV or station wagon. At a small scale this emoji is barely distinguishable from ğŸš— Automobile on some platforms.

name: Woman Dancing
description: A person dancing, most commonly displayed as woman with one arm raised wearing a red dress, while dancing the salsa or flamenco. Often used to represent a sense of fun or as a positive affirmation, e.g. "great! ğŸ’ƒ" This emoji did not originally specify a gender, but was canonically deemed a woman when the ğŸ•º Man Dancing emoji was approved . Google previously displayed this emoji as a man , then a gender-neutral blob character (in keeping with guidelines at the time). Microsoft previously displayed this emoji as stick figure , and Samsung has displayed this over various releases as a white boy , black boy , and white girl .
Woman Dancing was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name "Dancer" and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Womenâ€™s Room
description: A stick-figure icon of a woman, generally used to indicate a female restroom . The male equivalent is the Mens Symbol emoji.
Womenâ€™s Room was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name "Womens Symbol" and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Wood
description: One or two stumps of wood, cut so the rings are showing. Can be used to talk about wood or building materials. Also used in idioms with wood like knock on wood or out of the woods . Used to caption dic pics, often alongside the expression morning wood . Sometimes used in the context of games like Catan or Minecraft, where wood is a resource.
Wood was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Woozy Face
description: A yellow face with a crumpled mouth and a cockeyed expression, as if tired and emotional from inebriation or smitten with love. Depicted with raised or furrowed eyebrows and at least one eye half-open. WhatsApp's design features a tongue hanging out. Meaning widely varies, but commonly conveys intoxication or infatuation. Its dazed expression may also represent such feelings or states as bewilderment, irritation, disgust, exhaustion, wackiness, or complete satisfaction.
Woozy Face was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018 under the name "Face with Uneven Eyes and Wavy Mouth" and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

name: World Map
description: A rectangular map of the world. Generally depicted as a paper map creased at its folds, Earthâ€™s surface shown in green on blue ocean. Commonly represent maps, travel, exploration, and geography. May also represent various content concerning the world as a whole, e.g., global or international issues. Microsoft and Samsungâ€™s design previously depicted outlines of the continents.
World Map was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Worm
description: A pink or brown worm. Most platforms have more realistic designs, though Google and Samsung feature cartoony worms who are smiling sweetly. Can be used to talk about worms or disease spread by worms. Can also be used to refer to a deceitful person. May be used to in reference to the dance move 'the worm.'
Worm was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Worried Face
description: A yellow face with open eyes, raised or furrowed eyebrows, and a broad frown. May convey a variety of moderately sad or tense emotions, including concern, anxiety, alarm, disappointment, and unhappiness. Appleâ€™s design features the same eye expression as on its ğŸ˜¯ Hushed Face . Not to be confused with ğŸ˜²  Astonished Face or ğŸ˜µ Dizzy Face . Samsungâ€™s design previously included sweat droplets coming from its cheeks, a shorthand for anxiety in manga and anime.
Worried Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.1 in 2012 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Wrapped Gift
description: A present or gift in a box tied with a bow, as given on a birthday or Christmas . Box and ribbon color vary across platforms, but commonly depicted as a gold box with a lid wrapped with a red ribbon. Commonly used to represent gifts and presents on various holidays, celebrations, and special occasions. Samsungâ€™s design features a red ribbon tied around a blue box with white dots. WhatsAppâ€™s present is wrapped with blue paper and red ribbon.
Wrapped Gift was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name "Wrapped Present" and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Wrench
description: A metal wrench (spanner), as used for turning nuts and bolts . Depicted with two open, crescent-shaped ends or one open end and a closed, ring-shaped end. Generally positioned at a 45Â° angle. Commonly used for various content concerning tools, building, maintenance, and skilled trades like car mechanics and plumbing.
Wrench was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Writing Hand
description: A hand holding a pen or pencil and writing. Most often shown as holding either a blue or black pen, though Microsoft's design has a red pen. LG's design displays a left hand, while all other platforms show a right hand. Used broadly to represent writing. Also used between words to show that a lesson is being learned and to indicate someone is taking notes. For example, âœï¸lookâœï¸bothâœï¸waysâœï¸beforeâœï¸youâœï¸crossâœï¸theâœï¸street . This use was popularized in TikTok comments . It uses the established practice of placing emojis between words for emphasis. Possibly influenced by the emphatic use of ğŸ‘ Clapping Hands , which reflects speech-gesture pairings in Black English in the United States.
Writing Hand was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: X-Ray
description: An X-ray image. Most designs show a human thorax (including the rib cage and shoulder blades). Microsoft shows a skull , while X's design shows a hand . May be used to talk about X-rays or medicine in general.
X-Ray was approved as part of Unicode 14.0 in 2021 and added to Emoji 14.0 in 2021.

name: Yarn
description: A ball of yarn, as used to knit a scarf . Color varies across platforms, but often depicted in green, blue, or magenta and shown with an end unraveling. Sometimes depicted with a pair of knitting needles stuck in the ball. Commonly used for various content concerning knitting and needlework (e.g., sewing , crocheting), clothing and fashion, arts and crafts, cold weather, and cats.
Yarn was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018 under the name "Ball of Yarn" and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

name: Yawning Face
description: A yellow face with eyes closed and mouth wide open covered by a hand. Captured mid-yawn, this may represent having insufficient sleep, or to imply boredom with a person or topic. Not to be confused with ğŸ˜ª Sleepy Face or ğŸ˜´ Sleeping Face , which often convey actually being asleep, or ğŸ˜« Tired Face which is tired as in "fed up".
Yawning Face was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Yellow Circle
description: A circle shown in the color of yellow. As with other color-based shape emojis (most notably the hearts ), this emoji may be used to express an affinity with or appreciation for various people, places, groups, objects, or ideas associated with the same color.
Yellow Circle was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 under the name "Large Yellow Circle" and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Yellow Heart
description: A yellow or gold colored heart, frequently used alongside other colored hearts . Amusingly, this emoji displayed as a pink hairy heart on Android 4.4. It has been suggested that this visual oddity was created following a misinterpretation of Unicode's black-and-white reference images. As with the other color-based hearts, this emoji is often also used to express an affinity with or appreciation for various people, places, groups, objects, or ideas associated with the same color. This emoji is mentioned in the 2025 hit Netflix show Adolescence. Learn more here . On Snapchat , this emoji next to a contact denotes a person that you snap the most, and who also snaps you the most ( #1 best friend ). The yellow #1 BF heart turns into a red heart after two weeks.
Yellow Heart was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Yellow Square
description: A square shown in the color yellow. When players of the word game Wordle share their results on social platforms the results are represented through a series of green , yellow, and black or white square emojis. This emoji indicates that the player guessed a correct letter but in the wrong place within the word. This emoji is also often used to represent a y ellow penalty card in football (soccer) . Additionally, as with other color-based shape emojis (most notably the hearts ), this emoji may be used to express an affinity with or appreciation for various people, places, groups, objects, or ideas associated with the same color.
Yellow Square was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 under the name "Large Yellow Square" and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Yen Banknote

name: Yin Yang
description: The circular symbol frequently used to represent the concepts of yin and yang (also yinyang or yin-yang). The yin and yang symbol (or taijitu) shows a balance between two opposite but interconnected forces with a portion of the opposite element in each section.
Yin Yang was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

name: Zany Face
description: A yellow face with its head tilted, its tongue hanging out of a big grin, and wide eyes in a wild, cockeyed expression. Generally used to express silliness. Commonly represents acting goofy, having fun, and partying and is usually used in a positive manner. May be used in reference to someone or something that is off-kilter. Microsoft , and WhatsApp previously displayed a full-toothed grin instead of an open mouth with a protruding tongue, which appeared less silly and more menacing. Google's design used to show the mouth in a grimace, which also read as more disturbing than silly.
Zany Face was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017 under the name "Grinning Face with One Large and One Small Eye" and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.

name: Zombie
description: A reanimated human, often found in works of horror fiction. May have a female or male appearance. May be used to refer to someone who appears listless, apathetic, or unresponsive to their surroundings. May also be used to refer to a person who attempts to resume communications after previously ghosting out of a conversation.
Zombie was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017 and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017.
